{{Refimprove|date=September 2011}} {{Infobox Ethnic group |group=Julaha |population= |popplace = • India • Pakistan • England |langs = [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] • [[Hindi]] [[Urdu]] • [[Haryanvi]] • [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] |rels = [[Image:Om.svg|15px]] [[Hinduism]] • [[Image:Allah-green.svg|18px]] [[Islam]] • [[Image:Khanda.svg|15px]] [[Sikhism]] • [[Image:Cross-of-Christ.png|15px]] [[Christianity]]<ref>{{cite book | title=Culture, religion, and philosophy: critical studies in syncretism and inter-faith harmony | author=Nava Kishor Das | year=23 Jun 2009 | location=the University of Michigan | pages=374 pages | isbn=978-81-7033-820-8}}</ref> | related =other [[Ramdasia]] | }}
The '''Julaha''' are a community of [[Pakistan]] and [[India]], which adopted the profession of [[weaving]]. They are a sub category of Khatri people who are native of [[East Punjab]].
==Etymology== The term ''Julaha'' may derive from the Persian ''julah'' (ball of thread).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zQRuAAAAMAAJ|title=The scheduled castes|last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh|last2=India|first2=Anthropological Survey of|date=1993-01-01|publisher=Anthropological Survey of India|isbn=9780195632545|language=en}}</ref> Other explanation put forth by Julaha themselves include "''jal'' (net), ''jils'' (decorated) or ''uila'' (lighted up, or white)".
Both Hindu and Muslim Julaha groups exist; a number of the Muslim Julaha later changed their group name to terms such as ''[[Momin Ansari|Ansari]]''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fl53OdhuU7YC|title=Beyond Hindu and Muslim: Multiple Identity in Narratives from Village India|last=Gottschalk|first=Peter|date=2005-10-27|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199760527|language=en}}</ref> (the prophet Mohammed's term for the Muslims of [[Medina]]) or ''Nurbaf'' (''weaver of light''), Persian being a prestigious language amongst area Muslims).{{cn|date=April 2015}}
