The ''' Sedan Beehive stone huts''' are a [[provincial heritage site (South Africa)|provincial heritage site]] in [[Lindley, Free State|Lindley]] in the [[Free State (South African province)|Free State]] province of [[South Africa]].

In 1950 it was described in the [[Government Gazette of South Africa|Government Gazette]] as

{{quote|A group of pre-historic stone huts; the terrain contains remainings of a settlement from the early [[Sotho people|Sotho]] culture.<ref>[http://196.35.231.29/sahra/default.aspx South African Heritage Resource Agency database]</ref>}} 

These huts are near the farm Sedan which is about 13 kilometres west of Lindley. They include some of the best-preserved examples of these huts. The walls were built of stones packed without any mortar in such a manner that successive courses overlapped inwards until the opening at the apex was small enough to be closed by a single large slab. For obvious reasons, the huts were generally small. Few of them exceeded an internal diameter of 1.5 metres, and the height from floor to apex of the roof was barely 1,2 m. The only opening was the entrance at ground level usually about 45 cm high and 40 cm wide, so that it was necessary to enter the structure by crawling on one’s stomach.<ref>[http://www.sahra.org.za/sites/923260003 Beehive Stone Huts, Sedan, Lindley District]</ref>


